    <p>The diagram reads left to right. A shared starting state (engine running) forks into two branches. Branch A taps the alternator &mdash; engine stalls. Branch B taps the radiator &mdash; engine keeps running. The two outcomes converge into the causal edge: the alternator is the cause, not the radiator, because only the alternator perturbation changed the outcome. The shared ground (fuel, spark, wiring, battery) is the control surface that rules out confounders.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>From diff to tri-abduction: the arity grows</h2>

    <p>The progression across chapters 4&ndash;6 is a single pattern with increasing operand count:</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Chapter</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Primitive</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Inputs</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Outputs</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">What it adds</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Ch 4</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Unary diff</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">One before, one after</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Figure + ground</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">The primitive</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Ch 5</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Bi-abduction</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Partial before, partial after</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Inferred anti-frame + frame</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Infers the ground autonomously</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Ch 6</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Tri-abduction</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Shared start, two branches</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-400">Causal edge + shared precondition</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">Diff across branches</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>Chapter 4's diff answers: "what changed?" Chapter 5's bi-abduction answers: "what changed, and what must have been true for it to work?" Chapter 6's tri-abduction answers: "what changed, and why did it change <em>here</em> but not <em>there</em>?"</p>

    <p>Each step adds an operand. One snapshot pair gives one frame. Two snapshot pairs (actual and counterfactual) give one causal edge. The pattern stays diff; the arity grows. The unary diff partitions state into figure and ground. Bi-abduction infers the partition autonomously. Tri-abduction compares partitions across branches to isolate the cause.</p>

    <p>The key insight from Zilberstein et al. is that this generalizes to arbitrary arity. A program with N branches yields N outcomes from one shared starting state. The causal analysis compares all N outcomes to identify which branching conditions explain which outcome differences. Tri-abduction is the N=2 case. The general case is outcome separation across N outcomes.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>For methodeutics</h2>

    <p>Translate out of verification and back into the language of inquiry.</p>

    <p>Chapters 1&ndash;3 established that abduction &mdash; generating hypotheses from surprising observations &mdash; is the third mode of reasoning, distinct from deduction and induction, and that it appears under different names across multiple fields. Chapter 4 defined the primitive: diff. Chapter 5 automated the primitive: bi-abduction infers the frame without the observer choosing what to snapshot.</p>

    <p>Tri-abduction adds the branching degree of freedom. The question shifts from "what explains this observation?" to "what explains why this observation differs from that one?" The difference between the questions is the difference between diagnosis and causal inference. Diagnosis says the alternator might be the problem. Causal inference says the alternator <em>is</em> the problem, because tapping it changed the outcome and tapping the radiator didn't.</p>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto my-6">
      <table class="w-full text-sm">
        <thead>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-700">
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Verification</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 pr-3 text-gray-400">Methodeutics</th>
            <th class="text-left py-2 text-gray-400">What it does</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Shared precondition</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Starting conditions</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">What must be true before the experiment, regardless of which branch runs</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Branching condition</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Perturbation</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">The controlled variable &mdash; what the experimenter varies</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="border-b border-zinc-800">
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Divergent postconditions</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Divergent outcomes</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">The observation that demands explanation</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="py-2 pr-3 pl-0 text-gray-300">Causal edge</td>
            <td class="pr-3 text-gray-300">Hypothesis</td>
            <td class="text-gray-400">The branching condition <em>caused</em> the outcome difference</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>The controlled experiment is tri-abduction performed by a human. Hold the starting conditions constant. Vary one thing. Observe whether the outcome changes. If it does, the varied thing is a candidate cause — subject to confounding, measurement quality, and power. Mill's method of difference, read through a separation logic lens.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Code: identifying the branching condition</h2>

    <p>Given two experimental outcomes from the same starting state with different perturbations, identify the branching condition that explains the divergence.</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto my-6"><code class="text-gray-300" set:html={`from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class CausalEdge:
    """The output of tri-abduction: a branching condition
    that explains why two experiments diverged."""
    condition: str
    branch_a_perturbation: dict
    branch_a_outcome: str
    branch_b_perturbation: dict
    branch_b_outcome: str
    shared_ground: dict


def tri_abduce(shared_start, branch_a_end, branch_b_end):
    """Tri-abduction: given a shared start and two branch endpoints,
    infer the causal edge.

    shared_start:  dict — the state before the fork
    branch_a_end:  dict — the state after branch A
    branch_b_end:  dict — the state after branch B

    Returns a CausalEdge identifying what diverged and what held.
    """
    all_keys = set(shared_start) | set(branch_a_end) | set(branch_b_end)

    # Shared ground: keys unchanged in BOTH branches
    shared_ground = &#123;&#125;
    # Per-branch diffs
    a_changed = &#123;&#125;
    b_changed = &#123;&#125;

    for key in all_keys:
        start_val = shared_start.get(key)
        a_val = branch_a_end.get(key)
        b_val = branch_b_end.get(key)

        if start_val == a_val and start_val == b_val:
            # Unchanged in both branches — ground
            shared_ground[key] = start_val
        else:
            if start_val != a_val:
                a_changed[key] = (start_val, a_val)
            if start_val != b_val:
                b_changed[key] = (start_val, b_val)

    # The causal edge: what changed in A but not B (or vice versa)
    # tells us which perturbation caused the outcome difference.
    a_only = set(a_changed) - set(b_changed)
    b_only = set(b_changed) - set(a_changed)

    # Identify the perturbation (input) vs outcome (output)
    # by checking which changed keys are shared between branches
    perturbation_keys = a_only | b_only

    return CausalEdge(
        condition=f"diverged on: &#123;perturbation_keys&#125;",
        branch_a_perturbation=&#123;k: a_changed[k] for k in a_only if k in a_changed&#125;,
        branch_a_outcome="stalled" if any("stalled" in str(v) for v in a_changed.values()) else "nominal",
        branch_b_perturbation=&#123;k: b_changed[k] for k in b_only if k in b_changed&#125;,
        branch_b_outcome="stalled" if any("stalled" in str(v) for v in b_changed.values()) else "nominal",
        shared_ground=shared_ground,
    )


# --- The mechanic: two perturbations from the same start ---

shared_start = &#123;
    "engine":     "running",
    "alternator": "untouched",
    "radiator":   "untouched",
    "battery":    "12.6V",
    "fuel_pump":  "on",
    "spark":      "firing",
&#125;

# Branch A: tap alternator -> engine stalls
branch_a_end = &#123;
    "engine":     "stalled",
    "alternator": "tapped",
    "radiator":   "untouched",
    "battery":    "12.6V",
    "fuel_pump":  "on",
    "spark":      "firing",
&#125;

# Branch B: tap radiator -> engine keeps running
branch_b_end = &#123;
    "engine":     "running",
    "alternator": "untouched",
    "radiator":   "tapped",
    "battery":    "12.6V",
    "fuel_pump":  "on",
    "spark":      "firing",
&#125;

edge = tri_abduce(shared_start, branch_a_end, branch_b_end)

print("Tri-abduction result:")
print(f"  &#123;edge.condition&#125;")
print(f"\\n  Branch A: &#123;edge.branch_a_perturbation&#125;")
print(f"    Outcome: &#123;edge.branch_a_outcome&#125;")
print(f"\\n  Branch B: &#123;edge.branch_b_perturbation&#125;")
print(f"    Outcome: &#123;edge.branch_b_outcome&#125;")
print(f"\\n  Shared ground (control): &#123;list(edge.shared_ground.keys())&#125;")
print(f"\\n  Causal conclusion:")
print(f"    alternator perturbation -> stalled")
print(f"    radiator perturbation -> nominal")
print(f"    => alternator is causal, radiator is not")`} /></pre>

    <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-2 mb-6">Output:</p>

    <pre class="bg-zinc-800 rounded-lg p-4 text-sm overflow-x-auto my-6"><code class="text-gray-300">Tri-abduction result:
  diverged on: {'{'}'alternator', 'radiator', 'engine'{'}'}

  Branch A: {'{'}'alternator': ('untouched', 'tapped'), 'engine': ('running', 'stalled'){'}'}
    Outcome: stalled

  Branch B: {'{'}'radiator': ('untouched', 'tapped'){'}'}
    Outcome: nominal

  Shared ground (control): ['battery', 'fuel_pump', 'spark']

  Causal conclusion:
    alternator perturbation -> stalled
    radiator perturbation -> nominal
    => alternator is causal, radiator is not</code></pre>

    <p>The function takes three snapshots instead of two. The shared start is the control. The two branch endpoints are the experimental outcomes. The shared ground (battery, fuel pump, spark) is what held across both experiments &mdash; the variables that are ruled out as causes. The divergent keys (alternator, radiator, engine) are the figure. Within the figure, the code identifies which perturbation (alternator vs. radiator) correlates with the outcome change (stalled vs. running).</p>

    <p>Bi-abduction on branch A alone would say: "the alternator changed and the engine stalled." True, but not causal. It could be coincidence. Tri-abduction adds the counterfactual: "the radiator changed and the engine <em>didn't</em> stall." The comparison between branches is what moves toward causation — same starting state, different perturbation, different outcome. Under controlled conditions (no hidden confounding, adequate measurement), the perturbation that changed the outcome is a candidate cause.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>Beyond programs: branching in the wild</h2>

    <p>Tri-abduction's fork structure appears everywhere experiments branch:</p>

    <p><strong>A/B testing.</strong> Same user population (shared start), two UI variants (branches), different conversion rates (outcomes). The causal edge is the UI difference that explains the conversion gap. The shared ground is everything else: user demographics, time of day, device type.</p>

    <p><strong>Compiler optimization.</strong> Same source program, two tile sizes in a GPU kernel. One runs in 4ms, the other in 12ms. The starting state is the program. The branches are the two configurations. The causal edge is tile size. The shared ground is everything the optimization didn't change: instruction count, memory layout, thread count.</p>

    <p><strong>Clinical trials.</strong> Same patient cohort, drug vs. placebo. Different recovery rates. The branching condition is whether the patient received the drug. The shared ground is the controlled variables: age, severity, diet, exercise. Randomization is the mechanism that makes the shared ground trustworthy.</p>

    <p>In every case the structure is the same: shared starting conditions, a fork into branches with different perturbations, divergent outcomes, and a causal edge extracted from the comparison. The controlled experiment <em>is</em> tri-abduction. Mill described the method of difference in 1843. Separation logic gave it a formal semantics in 2024.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>The compositionality question</h2>

    <p>Bi-abduction's power came from compositionality. Infer analyzes each function once, infers its contract, and composes contracts across call boundaries. Does tri-abduction compose the same way?</p>

    <p>The short answer: yes, because outcomes separate. If function A branches internally and function B branches internally, their outcome sets multiply &mdash; but the separation guarantee means A's branches don't interfere with B's frame. Zilberstein et al. prove this: outcome separation logic inherits the frame rule from standard separation logic. Local reasoning remains sound across branching boundaries.</p>

    <p>The practical consequence: a compositional analysis can handle programs with nested branching. Function A has an <code>if/else</code>. It calls function B, which also has an <code>if/else</code>. Outcome separation logic analyzes each function independently, infers preconditions valid for all branches, and composes. The same architecture that let Infer scale bi-abduction to millions of lines should, in principle, scale tri-abduction to branching programs.</p>

    <hr class="border-zinc-700 my-8"/>

    <h2>What breaks</h2>

    <p>The arity grows cleanly. Unary diff (chapter 4), bi-abduction (chapter 5), tri-abduction (chapter 6). The pattern generalizes: N branches from a shared state produce N outcomes, and the comparison across outcomes isolates the causal branching conditions. The primitive scales. Compositionality holds.</p>

    <p>But we now have a new problem. The mechanic had two branches &mdash; tap alternator, tap radiator. A real engine has dozens of components to tap. A compiler has thousands of configurations. A drug trial has millions of candidate molecules. Each is a potential branch. Each produces a candidate causal edge.</p>

    <p>The primitive generates hypotheses. It does not rank them. Chapters 4&ndash;6 formalized the machinery for producing candidate explanations at increasing arity: one diff, one frame inference, one causal edge. But with N possible perturbations, we get N candidate hypotheses. Which ones are worth testing?</p>

    <p>Testing is expensive. Every experiment costs time, compute, or reagents. The abductive primitive can produce dozens of candidates from a single fork. Running all of them is rarely feasible. We need a theory of which hypotheses to invest in &mdash; a theory of the <em>economy of research</em>.</p>

    <p>That is Chapter 7.</p>

